      <!-- Why ChatGPT gets this wrong -->
      <section class="compare-content-block">
        <h2 class="compare-section__heading" style="font-size:1.4rem;">Why ChatGPT gets this wrong</h2>
        <p>ChatGPT is <strong>trained to be helpful</strong>. "Helpful" means validating your intent, answering your question, and assisting you in accomplishing what you're trying to do. For almost every message you paste in, the helpful response is "go ahead and send it, here's how to phrase it better." That's not a flaw — it's what it's designed for. But when you're spiraling at 11 PM, <strong>"helpful" is the last thing you need.</strong></p>
        <p>Harvard Business Review identified therapy/companionship as the <strong>#1 use case for generative AI</strong> in 2025. People are using ChatGPT for mental health support — and it's not built for it. A family is suing OpenAI, alleging ChatGPT contributed to their 16-year-old's suicide. Stanford's 2025 research shows AI therapist chatbots have "significantly lower effectiveness" than human therapists.</p>
        <p><strong>HoldOff's only job is to stop you from sending the wrong text. That's the whole product.</strong></p>
      </section>

